{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"dd65182c-b9b5-405b-be05-bb5cf736fd76","content":"TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively, so you pass the `--treenode-filter` argument after `--`:\n\n```bash\ndotnet test -- --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nThe treenode filter path format is `/Assembly/Namespace/Class/Test`. The wildcards match any assembly and namespace, filtering to just the `SmsNotificationTests` class and all its tests (`SendSms_HealthCheck`, `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9bf1916c-5058-43cd-9b36-c4fc2dffd7ea","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For TUnit with MTP, the filter syntax is different from VSTest. TUnit uses `--treenode-filter` for filtering tests.\n\nFor TUnit, to filter by class name, the command would use `--treenode-filter` with the appropriate syntax. The treenode filter for a class in TUnit uses the format:\n\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests/*\"\n```\n\nOr alternatively, TUnit supports `--filter` with the FullyQualifiedName:\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. \n\nThe treenode filter path pattern for TUnit follows `/AssemblyName/Namespace/ClassName/TestName`, so filtering by the `SmsNotificationTests` class would use the wildcard pattern to match all tests within it. I need to clarify whether `dotnet test` works directly with MTP runners or if it requires `dotnet run` instead, since MTP-based runners sometimes need different invocation methods.","outputTokens":609,"requestId":"BD02:158C5C:2184C02:261B93B:6A07E0F9"},"id":"adcd9a83-b7a6-469e-8c7a-2c3853504d5c","timestamp":"2026-05-16T03:14:15.051Z","parentId":"33766454-b4de-4ac6-9c71-08a0a3757abc"}
